@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "egoPdf — coded PDFs, perfect on paper";
}

@*
    Landing images live in wwwroot/img/landing-*.png. The original
    image-agent prompts that produced them sit at the bottom of this
    file inside a Razor comment, so any future re-generation can reuse
    the exact wording (palette, aspect, file path).
*@

<section class="text-center py-5">
    <div class="container">
        <img src="~/img/logo.png" alt="egoPdf"
             class="img-fluid mb-4" style="max-height: 200px;" />
        <h1 class="display-4 fw-light mb-2">
            Coded PDFs, <span class="text-coral">perfect on paper</span>.
        </h1>
        <p class="lead text-muted mb-4">
            A .NET library family for millimetric PDF layout.
            Agent-friendly. Ruler-grade. Pure MIT.
        </p>
        <div class="d-flex gap-2 justify-content-center flex-wrap">
            <a asp-page="/Examples" class="btn btn-dark btn-lg px-4">
                See the examples
            </a>
            <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages?q=EgoPDF"
               target="_blank" rel="noopener"
               class="btn btn-outline-dark btn-lg px-4">
                NuGet
            </a>
            <a href="https://github.com/marcoregueira/egopdf"
               target="_blank" rel="noopener"
               class="btn btn-outline-dark btn-lg px-4">
                GitHub
            </a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="py-5 border-top">
    <div class="container">
    <div class="row align-items-center g-5">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <img src="~/img/landing-hero.png"
                 alt="C# code on the left transforming into a printed PDF on the right with ruler and pencil overlay."
                 class="img-fluid rounded shadow-sm" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2 class="mb-3">Pixel-perfect PDFs in C#</h2>
            <p class="lead text-muted">
                Imperative control over every cell, every millimetre,
                with no PHP detour. SkiaSharp underneath for accurate
                font metrics; SourceLink and symbol packages for clean
                debugging.
            </p>
            <ul class="text-muted">
                <li>The 14 PDF core fonts ship out of the box &mdash; no TTF needed for "Hello World".</li>
                <li>Embed any TrueType with a single <code>LoadFont</code> call.</li>
                <li>Output validates cleanly in Acrobat, Chrome and the major PDF viewers.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="py-5 bg-light">
    <div class="container">
    <div class="row align-items-center g-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <img src="~/img/landing-primitives.png"
                 alt="Diagram of an A4 page being carved into rows, columns and a titled panel with Row/Stack/Panel labels."
                 class="img-fluid rounded shadow-sm" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2 class="mb-3">Layout that reads like the page it draws</h2>
            <p class="lead text-muted">
                <code>Row</code>, <code>Stack</code> and <code>Panel</code>
                compose a page without the <code>x + width + gap</code>
                arithmetic. The call site reads as the layout it produces.
            </p>
<pre class="border rounded p-3 bg-white small mb-0"><code>var cols = pdf.Row(pdf.Bounds(), new[] { 2.0, 1.0 }, gap: 3);
pdf.Panel(cols[0], "DETAILS", brandStyle, content =&gt; {
    // body lives inside `content`,
    // state restored on return
});</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="py-5 border-top">
    <div class="container">
    <div class="row align-items-center g-5">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <img src="~/img/landing-mixed-mode.png"
                 alt="A4 page split into a dark brand header band on top and a clean Markdown body with stylised paragraphs and a coral block-quote bar."
                 class="img-fluid rounded shadow-sm" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2 class="mb-3">Markdown and ruler-grade drawing on the same page</h2>
            <p class="lead text-muted">
                Render CommonMark + GFM through <code>EgoPDF.Markdown</code>,
                drop into native code where the visual demands it. The
                shortcode extension is the bridge.
            </p>
            <ul class="text-muted">
                <li>Headings, lists, code blocks, links, autolinks, quotes, images.</li>
                <li><code>[[barcode]]</code>, <code>[[image]]</code>, <code>[[cta]]</code>, <code>[[imagepair]]</code>
                    &mdash; each block shortcode dispatches to a handler you control.</li>
                <li>Imperative header bands compose with Markdown bodies in the same FPdf instance.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="py-5 bg-light">
    <div class="container">
    <div class="row align-items-center g-5 flex-md-row-reverse">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <img src="~/img/landing-agent.png"
                 alt="Abstract geometric agent figure holding a printed A4 page next to a wooden ruler and pencil."
                 class="img-fluid rounded shadow-sm" />
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2 class="mb-3">Friendly for humans <em>and</em> agents</h2>
            <p class="lead text-muted">
                Single-method primitives, scope helpers that auto-restore
                state, declarative styling records and a copy-pasteable
                recipe catalog. An LLM agent can derive everything it
                needs from the same shipping samples a developer reads.
            </p>
            <ul class="text-muted">
                <li><code>using (pdf.PushState())</code> / <code>PushPos()</code> &mdash; mutate freely, revert on exit.</li>
                <li><code>PanelStyle</code> records capture frame + title looks as reusable data.</li>
                <li><a href="https://github.com/marcoregueira/egopdf/blob/master/RECIPES.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">RECIPES.md</a>
                    indexes every pattern with pointers into the source samples.</li>
                <li>SHA-256 visual baselines catch unintended drift between refactors.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="py-5 border-top">
    <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Three packages, all MIT</h2>
    <div class="row g-3">
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="border rounded p-3 h-100 text-center">
                <h5 class="mb-1">
                    <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/EgoPDF.Generator/"
                       target="_blank" rel="noopener">EgoPDF.Generator</a>
                </h5>
                <p class="text-muted small mb-0">
                    Core PDF engine with the layout primitives.
                    Depends on SkiaSharp.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="border rounded p-3 h-100 text-center">
                <h5 class="mb-1">
                    <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/EgoPDF.Barcodes/"
                       target="_blank" rel="noopener">EgoPDF.Barcodes</a>
                </h5>
                <p class="text-muted small mb-0">
                    Every 1D / 2D symbology through ZXing.Net,
                    plus a ZPL II emulator.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
            <div class="border rounded p-3 h-100 text-center">
                <h5 class="mb-1">
                    <a href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/EgoPDF.Markdown/"
                       target="_blank" rel="noopener">EgoPDF.Markdown</a>
                </h5>
                <p class="text-muted small mb-0">
                    CommonMark + GFM via Markdig, rendered through
                    EgoPDF.Generator.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="text-center py-5 border-top">
    <div class="container">
    <h2 class="mb-3">Ready to render?</h2>
    <p class="text-muted mb-4">
        See the live examples or grab the packages from NuGet.
    </p>
    <div class="d-flex gap-2 justify-content-center flex-wrap">
        <a asp-page="/Examples" class="btn btn-dark btn-lg px-4">
            Live examples
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/marcoregueira/egopdf"
           target="_blank" rel="noopener"
           class="btn btn-outline-dark btn-lg px-4">
            GitHub
        </a>
    </div>
    </div>
</section>

@*
    Image-agent prompts that produced the four landing-*.png files in
    wwwroot/img/. Kept here so a future regeneration (different agent,
    different aspect, dark-mode variant, ...) can reuse the exact wording
    instead of redrafting from scratch. Shared constraints across all
    four: brand palette dark #1A1D26 + coral #CC695F + muted #6E7382,
    white background, no people, no readable text inside the image, 16:9
    aspect (1600x900 works).

    --- 1. wwwroot/img/landing-hero.png (hero banner) ---
    A clean, minimalist illustration in flat-vector style. Left half:
    a stylised IDE window showing a few lines of C# code (just the
    shapes, no readable text), with a coral cursor blinking on one
    line. An arrow flows from the IDE rightwards. Right half: an A4
    printed PDF page sitting on a desk with a wooden ruler and a
    pencil resting on it, with subtle horizontal lines suggesting
    rendered paragraphs. Editorial, calm tone.

    --- 2. wwwroot/img/landing-primitives.png (layout diagram) ---
    A diagrammatic illustration of layout primitives. Centre stage:
    a stylised A4 page (portrait) being carved into a 2x3 grid by
    faint coral lines. Two top cells hold simple bullet-list icons,
    one middle cell holds a small bar-chart, one cell holds a QR
    code placeholder, the bottom row is a single wide panel with a
    small title bar and three rows of placeholder content. Floating
    labels in muted grey monospace next to relevant cells:
    "Row(bounds, n)" beside a horizontal split, "Stack(bounds, w)"
    beside a vertical split, "Panel(bounds, title)" beside the wide
    bottom panel. Flat-vector, technical-but-friendly.

    --- 3. wwwroot/img/landing-mixed-mode.png (mixed-mode document) ---
    A single stylised A4 page split horizontally. Top third: a dark
    brand header band (#1A1D26 fill) with a small white-and-coral
    wordmark in the top-left corner and a right-aligned bold title
    suggestion. Bottom two thirds: a clean white area showing
    stylised Markdown content -- two heading bars, a few paragraph
    lines (just horizontal strokes), a bullet list of three items,
    and a coral block-quote bar on the left. Thin coral hairline
    bridges the dark band and the markdown area. Editorial design tone.

    --- 4. wwwroot/img/landing-agent.png (agent-friendly mark) ---
    A friendly minimalist scene: an abstract wireframe robot or
    geometric agent figure (think simple cube or sphere with a
    single coral eye-dot, not a humanoid) holding a printed A4
    page that shows faint horizontal lines suggesting rendered
    text plus a small QR code in the corner. A pencil and a wooden
    ruler rest beside the figure. Generous whitespace.
*@
